## Slide 1: The Bottleneck Blocking Britain's Energy Transition

The UK has **legally binding targets**: clean power by 2030, net zero by 2050. Delivering them requires consenting **~100GW** of new energy infrastructure through the planning system.

**The planning system cannot cope.**

| Metric | Reality |
|--------|---------|
| Grid connection queue | **733 GW** waiting (National Grid ESO, 2024) — 7x what the UK actually needs |
| Avg. NSIP consent timeline | **4.2 years** from application to decision — double the statutory target |
| NSIP applications in system | **130+** nationally significant projects, each generating **10,000–50,000 pages** of documents |
| Planning appeal decisions (all types) | **~15,000/year** from the Planning Inspectorate alone |
| Government response | NSIP Action Plan (2023), Planning Reform Bill, Electricity Networks Commissioner — all identify consenting speed as the **#1 blocker** |

The consultants, lawyers, and developers navigating this system still work by **manually reading PDFs**. There is no semantic search, no cross-project analysis, no structured precedent database.

> *"The consenting process is the single greatest risk to the UK's energy security."*
> — Electricity Networks Commissioner Report, 2023

